\subsection{\label{ssec:frametheory}Connection to Frame Theory}

Since our construction of perceptually motivated FBs emphasizes stable reconstruction from the FB coefficients, it seems worthwhile to mention that inversion of non-uniform FBs can also be investigated using frame theory, the mathematical theory of stable, redundant spanning sets of functions. For uniform FBs, this connection has been explored in depth (e.g. \cite{Bolcskei:1998a,Cvetkovic:1998a,Fickus:2013a,badokowto13}). For non-uniform FBs, the connections have, to our knowledge, not been stated explicitly in the literature although implicitly used in recent work (e.g. \cite{Holighaus:2013a},\cite{Bayram:2013a}). A frame over the space of finite energy sequences $\ell_2(\mathbb Z)$ is a (possibly redundant) family of functions spanning the space in a stable fashion, in the sense of inequality \eqref{eq:framineq1} below. The central observation linking FBs to frames is that

